  "prompt": "What are the symptoms of eczema?",
  "response": "Eczema, also known as atopic dermatitis, is a chronic skin condition characterized by a variety of symptoms, which can vary in severity and may include:\n\n1. **Itching:** Often intense and persistent, itching is a primary symptom of eczema. Scratching can worsen the condition.\n\n2. **Redness:** The affected skin often appears red and inflamed.\n\n3. **Dry Skin:** Eczema typically causes dry, scaly skin that can crack and even bleed.\n\n4. **Rash:** May appear on different parts of the body, often in the creases of the elbows, knees, and around the neck. In infants, it can show up on the face and scalp.\n\n5. **Thickened Skin:** Continuous scratching can cause the skin to become thickened or leathery over time (known as lichenification).\n\n6. **Swelling:** Inflamed areas might become swollen.\n\n7. **Blisters:** Some cases may present small, fluid-filled blisters that can ooze and form crusts when they break.\n\n8. **Crusting and Oozing:** When the affected skin becomes severely irritated, it may ooze fluid and crust over.\n\n9. **Pigmentation Changes:** Eczema can cause lighter or darker skin patches due to inflammation or healing.\n\n10. **Sensitive Skin:** Affected areas might be more sensitive and easily irritated by various factors, including soaps, detergents, and environmental factors.\n\nKeeping the skin moisturized, avoiding triggers, and using prescribed medications or treatments can help manage these symptoms. If you suspect that you or someone else has eczema, it\u2019s advisable to consult a healthcare provider for a proper diagnosis and treatment plan.",
